<p><b>Wednesday, May 14, 2003</b></p>

	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="13"></a>1.1 - Persistent Worlds: Toward what Future?</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:00 AM<br />
			Room: 411<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Persistent world gaming is one of the fastest-
growing and sectors in the game industry. This 
session will ask an international panel of 
designers and publishers of MMOL games to discuss 
what was learned from the first generation of 
persistent world games, what they tried to 
accomplish with their own MMOL titles, and how 
the genre will advance in the coming years.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Jessica Mulligan,&nbsp;The Themis Group&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Jeff Anderson,&nbsp;Turbine Entertainment Software&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Marc Jacobs,&nbsp;Mythic Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Philip Rosedale,&nbsp;Linden Labs&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="19"></a>2.1 - Big Money: How Big Ideas and Global Corporations are Changing the Face of Gaming</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:00 AM<br />
			Room: 404AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			As the games industry grows, it becomes a more 
and more attractive sector for outside business 
concerns to enter. Which large corporations are 
moving into the games turf, what's the agenda 
behind their entry, and will their presence 
change the industry? This panel will investigate 
how companies (such as Intel, Yahoo!, Disney, 
IBM, and Nokia) view the game industry, and how 
their increased investment in the sector is 
affecting it.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Amy Bernstein,&nbsp;Business 2.0&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Charles Hirschhorn,&nbsp;G4 Media&nbsp;<br />
						
							  David Mandelbrot,&nbsp;Yahoo! Inc.&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="27"></a>3.1 - Reaching the New Gamer</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:00 AM<br />
			Room: 406AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			With 60 percent of gamers now over 18, it’s only 
a matter of time before that age skews older – 
and older. Sooner or later, this shift in 
demographics will force publishers to release 
content to meet the demand of these new, more 
mature consumers. How will the market expand and 
what demographic groups will dominate? What 
genres will survive, what genres will fade away, 
and what new genres will be created? How can 
developers and publishers target their message to 
the right audience for a given title? And how 
should the industry react to the growing 
popularity of mature-themed games.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Jason Rubin,&nbsp;Naughty Dog, Inc.&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Vince Broady,&nbsp;GameSpot&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="33"></a>4.1 - Hired Guns: The New Talent Pool and How to Fit In</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:00 AM<br />
			Room: 408B<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			The game industry has always used freelance 
writers and musicians, but is increasingly 
turning to independent artists, designers, and 
producers for help as well. Is the Hollywood 
model of a large pool of freelance talent right 
for the games industry - or just inevitable?  
What should a publisher or developer consider 
when hiring freelance talent, and where can they 
find it? How does a talented freelancer best 
operate within this new structure? How do we as 
an industry borrow on the production disciplines 
from Hollywood to create a more sustainable (and 
predictable) growth curve? Come away from this 
session with a better understanding of how 
outside talent is changing the way games are 
produced, and how to manage your studio or 
publishing company to take advantage of this 
change.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Noah Falstein,&nbsp;The Inspiracy&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Nick Desemov,&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Ken Goldstein,&nbsp;Disney Interactive&nbsp;<br />
						
							  American McGee,&nbsp;Carbon6 Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="14"></a>1.2 - Design Secrets: Online -- USA and Asia</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 11:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;1:00 PM<br />
			Room: 411<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Asia is always a leader in defining what’s 
bright, creative, fun, and compelling about games 
and game culture. Our Design Secrets series 
continues its popular run at E3. Last year, Will 
Wright and Yu Suzuki shared their unique 
perspectives, as did Peter Molyneux and Bruce 
Shelley. This year, we will pick two panelists 
from the MMOL space, and will announce the 
special pairing soon.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Raph Koster,&nbsp;Sony Online Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="20"></a>2.2 - A Global Tour of Top Games, Genres, and Trends</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 11:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;1:00 PM<br />
			Room: 404AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			In Korea, more than 20,000 game rooms are filled 
with networked PCs and devoted gamers. In Japan, 
a spike in the number of games targeting girls is 
testing the traction games have with women. And 
in Finland, mobile technology has created the 
unique location-based game genre. Take note: 
today’s best-selling game in Asia or Europe can 
be tomorrow’s blockbuster hit in America, so it 
pays to stay in touch with the chart-topping 
games in these foreign markets. Our panel will 
focus on the most creative and popular games the 
world over and look at what’s behind their 
success.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Sven Halling,&nbsp;It's Alive&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Dejian Liu,&nbsp;NetDragon&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Starr Long,&nbsp;NCsoft&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="28"></a>3.2 - Marketing Solutions for Every Budget</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 11:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;1:00 PM<br />
			Room: 406AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			How do you create and execute an effective 
marketing and promotion campaign that works with 
your game’s unique content and company’s fixed 
budget? Maybe    you want your ads on network TV, 
but can you afford it? You might want your game 
previewed in Time and Entertainment Weekly, but 
do you know who to call? And how would you 
narrowcast a message to the enthusiast community 
for a game that is too niche for mainstream press 
or TV? A panel of marketing experts will use 
three hypothetical budgets – $20,000, $250,000, 
and $1 million -- and discuss the best methods to 
promote a game, create brand awareness, and drive 
sales within the limitations of each.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Liz Allen,&nbsp;LucasArts Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="34"></a>4.2 - Music Matters</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 11:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;1:00 PM<br />
			Room: 408B<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			It's not just graphics and storyline that 
determine which games get talked about. More and 
more, it's the game's soundtrack that contributes 
to the splash it makes with the media, gamers, 
and retail. This panel will give attendees an 
understanding of how to use music to reach a 
specific, targeted demographic -- and will look 
at titles which successfully engaged gamers by 
the inclusion of top-quality music (think Tony 
Hawk and Grand Theft Auto). Learn how to match 
the right music with your game, how deals are 
structured, and how to find talent. The session 
will also address the reciprocal benefit record 
companies derive from their involvement in the 
game industry, how this relationship will likely 
grow, and how you can leverage the recording 
industry’s desire to ally with the game business.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Germaine Gioia,&nbsp;THQ, Inc.&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Steve Schnur,&nbsp;Electronic Arts&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="15"></a>1.3 - Consoles Go Online: First Semester Grades</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 1:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
			Room: 411<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			2002 will be known as the year consoles went 
online. This panel of hardware executives will 
discuss their company's online game strategy from 
launch to the present. What lessons can be 
learned from the first half year online? What 
percentage of games is expected to have an online 
component? And when can we expect a fully 
functional persistent world experience from 
consoles? The panel will also discuss plans and 
strategies for their next year online. Hear what 
went right, what went wrong, and what's ahead 
from the players themselves. <br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="21"></a>2.3 - You Asked For It</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 1:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
			Room: 404AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Each year we ask past and future attendees to 
recommend a topic to be covered in the upcoming 
program. Or there may be an individual from the 
creative or corporate ranks you’d like to see 
interviewed in a one-on-one situation. As always, 
we are open to your ideas. Send your suggestions 
to conferenceadmin@e3xpo.com by April 1 for 
consideration<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="29"></a>3.3 - Analyst Roundtable: How they Work, What they Know</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 1:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
			Room: 406AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			You spend your time making games, they spend 
their time analyzing the marketplace. Isn’t it 
time you listened to what they have to say about 
which publishers have the best strategies, which 
platforms will find traction with consumers, and 
what retail models will prevail? Hear from the 
industry's top analysts as they discuss where the 
game business is headed. Understand their 
methodologies (to better analyze the marketplace 
yourself) as you hear them assess trends, sales 
figures, and industry growth.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Alex Pham,&nbsp;Los Angeles Times&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
				<tr>
					<td valign="top">Panelists:</td>
					<td>&nbsp;</td>
					<td valign="top">
						
							  Richard Ow,&nbsp;NPD/Funworld&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Michael Pachter,&nbsp;Wedbush Morgan Securities&nbsp;<br />
						
							  Edward Williams,&nbsp;Gerard Klauer Mattison&nbsp;<br />
						
					</td>
				</tr>
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="35"></a>4.3 - Sneak Peeks: Taking the Wraps off the Hottest New Titles</b><br />
			Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 1:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
			Room: 408B<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Last year’s Sneak Peeks session marked the first 
public demos of three of the industry’s most 
anticipated games: Doom III, C&C Generals, and 
Star Wars: Bounty Hunter. This year, we’ll get 
under the skin of three new games still in 
development. Learn how the top pros manage the 
game development process and hear how they juggle 
the needs of their team, their publisher, and the 
media. Always accompanied by playable code, Sneak 
Peeks is designed to inform by presenting a 
unique window into the game development process. 
Ask questions, take notes, and learn how the top 
designers handle the pressures of developing AAA 
product – and use that knowledge to make you own 
game development process that much more 
efficient. We will update the e3expo.com web site 
with more specifics as they are known.<br />
		
		</p>
			
